          "title": "'Holy to the LORD' — the inscription that defines everything",
          "body": "Of all the chapter's details, the most theologically concentrated is the four-word inscription on the high priest's golden forehead plate: 'Holy to the LORD' (39:30). This formula — qodesh la-Yehovah — declares that the person wearing it is separated from all common use and consecrated exclusively to Yahweh. It is the ultimate definition of the priestly vocation. The plate is fastened to the turban with a blue cord (39:31), so that it rests above Aaron's brow — visible, permanent, identifying. Whatever else the high priest is doing, he is publicly and perpetually declared holy to the covenant God. The New Testament reader cannot but notice that Jesus, Israel's great high priest (Hebrews 4:14), bears this identity not on a golden plate but in His very nature: He is 'holy, innocent, undefiled, separated from sinners, and exalted above the heavens' (Hebrews 7:26) — the living fulfillment of the inscription that Exodus 39 hammers into pure gold."
